    <!-- SLIDE 1 -->
    <div class="slide active">
        <h1>Learning From Complex Cases</h1>
        <h2>82-Year-Old Male with Recurrent Pneumonia</h2>
        <div class="box" style="margin-top:30px;">
            <h3>Learning Objectives</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Develop systematic chart review approaches</li>
                <li>Recognize infection risk in CLL</li>
                <li>Apply clinical reasoning when labs diverge from clinical picture</li>
                <li>Implement antibiotic stewardship</li>
                <li>Identify quality improvement opportunities</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="warning" style="margin-top:30px;">
            <p><strong>Note:</strong> Real de-identified case focused on learning and systems improvement.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SLIDE 2 -->
    <div class="slide">
        <h1>Initial Presentation</h1>
        <div class="box">
            <h3>Chief Complaint</h3>
            <p style="font-size:1.3em;font-weight:bold;">"Altered mental status, breathing problem"</p>
        </div>
        <div class="box">
            <h3>Timeline</h3>
            <p><strong>Day -8 (First Admission):</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Neighbor found patient confused, SOB × several days</li>
                <li>Unable to provide history (dementia)</li>
                <li>CXR: Bibasilar opacities</li>
                <li>Started IV antibiotics, improved</li>
            </ul>
            <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>Day 5:</strong> Left AMA - "Tired of hospital"</p>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>48 hours later:</strong> Re-presentation</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Found somnolent, SpO2 84%</li>
                <li>Initially hypotensive (BP 65/45)</li>
                <li>Transferred to our facility</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <p><strong>Context:</strong> Lives alone, progressive dementia, medication non-compliance, still driving</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SLIDE 3 -->
    <div class="slide">
        <h1>Laboratory Data (Day 1)</h1>
        <h3>Complete Blood Count</h3>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Test</th><th>Value</th><th>Reference</th></tr>
            <tr><td>WBC</td><td class="high">13.61 K/µL</td><td>4.23-9.07</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Hemoglobin</td><td class="low">10.8 g/dL</td><td>13.7-17.5</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Hematocrit</td><td class="low">33.4%</td><td>40.1-51.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Platelets</td><td>220 K/µL</td><td>163-337</td></tr>
        </table>
        <p><em>Hemoglobin documented as "at baseline"</em></p>
        <h3 style="margin-top:25px;">Renal Function</h3>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Test</th><th>Value</th><th>Reference</th></tr>
            <tr><td>BUN</td><td class="high">39 mg/dL</td><td>8-23</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Creatinine</td><td class="high">2.60 mg/dL</td><td>0.67-1.17</td></tr>
            <tr><td>eGFR</td><td class="low">24 mL/min</td><td>>60</td></tr>
        </table>
        <div class="box" style="margin-top:20px;">
            <p><strong>Additional:</strong> Troponin 27→31→32 (stable) | BNP 3,743 | Procalcitonin 0.07 | Virals negative</p>
        </div>
        <div class="warning">
            <p><strong>Pattern:</strong> Leukocytosis + chronic anemia + very low procalcitonin. What does this suggest?</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SLIDE 4 -->
    <div class="slide">
        <h1>CT Chest Findings</h1>
        <div class="success"><p><strong>Finding #1:</strong> No acute pulmonary embolism ✓</p></div>
        <div class="box">
            <p><strong>Finding #2:</strong> RLL consolidation + scattered ground-glass opacities → Pneumonia ± aspiration</p>
        </div>
        <div class="critical">
            <h3>Finding #3: THE CRITICAL OBSERVATION</h3>
            <p style="font-size:1.2em;margin:15px 0;font-style:italic;">
                "Constellation of findings suggestive of <strong>lymphomatous disorder</strong> with multiple areas of <strong>lymphadenopathy</strong> in chest and upper abdomen"
            </p>
            <p><strong>Locations:</strong> Axillary (bilateral), Mediastinal, Hilar (bilateral), Retroperitoneal, Porta hepatis</p>
            <p style="font-size:1.3em;margin-top:15px;"><strong>= GENERALIZED LYMPHADENOPATHY</strong></p>
        </div>
        <p style="text-align:center;font-size:1.3em;font-weight:bold;margin-top:30px;color:#e74c3c;">
            The radiologist is telling us: lymphoproliferative disorder
        </p>
    </div>

    <!-- SLIDE 5 -->
    <div class="slide">
        <h1>What Was Actually in the Chart</h1>
        <div class="critical">
            <h2>Hematology Note from 3 Months Prior (August 2025)</h2>
            <p>Comprehensive note - 11 weeks before admission</p>
        </div>
        <div class="warning" style="margin-top:20px;">
            <h3>Established Diagnosis</h3>
            <p style="font-size:1.4em;font-weight:bold;color:#e74c3c;">Small Lymphocytic Lymphoma / Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia (SLL/CLL)</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Diagnosed:</strong> July 2024 (16 months prior)</li>
                <li><strong>Stage:</strong> Lugano Stage III (above & below diaphragm)</li>
                <li><strong>Treatment:</strong> Active surveillance (watch & wait)</li>
                <li><strong>Last hematology visit:</strong> August 2025</li>
                <li><strong>Due for follow-up:</strong> November 2025 (when he got admitted!)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="box" style="margin-top:20px;">
            <h3>Complete Diagnostic Workup on File</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Flow cytometry: 90% clonal B-cells (CD19+, CD5+, CD23+, dim lambda)</li>
                <li>Kappa:Lambda ratio: 0.01 (markedly restricted, normal ~2:1)</li>
                <li>PET CT: Confirmed Stage III disease</li>
                <li>FISH: ATM deletion, 13q14.2</li>
                <li>IGVH: Non-mutated</li>
                <li>August labs: WBC 7.34, <strong>Absolute Lymphocyte Count 3.48</strong> (elevated baseline)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SLIDE 6 -->
    <div class="slide">
        <h1>Hospital Course: Days 2-3</h1>
        <div class="success">
            <h3>Day 2 - Dramatic Clinical Improvement</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Weaned to room air</strong> ✓</li>
                <li>Afebrile throughout ✓</li>
                <li>Hemodynamically stable ✓</li>
                <li>No symptoms ✓</li>
                <li>Echo: EF 60-65%, no vegetation</li>
                <li>Troponin flat - demand ischemia</li>
                <li>Cr: 2.60 → 2.31 (improving)</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Antibiotics:</strong> Ceftriaxone + Azithromycin (Day 1/5)</p>
        </div>
        <div class="warning" style="margin-top:20px;">
            <h3>Day 3 - Laboratory Change</h3>
            <p><strong>Clinical:</strong> SpO2 95% RA, afebrile, stable, wants to go home</p>
            <table style="margin-top:15px;">
                <tr><th>Test</th><th>Day 1</th><th>Day 3</th><th>Change</th></tr>
                <tr><td>WBC</td><td>13.61</td><td class="high">14.98</td><td>↑ 10%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Hgb</td><td>10.8</td><td class="low">9.9</td><td>↓ 8%</td></tr>
            </table>
        </div>
        <div class="critical" style="margin-top:20px;">
            <h3>Decision Made</h3>
            <p><strong>Antibiotic Escalation:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Discontinued ceftriaxone + azithromycin (after only 1 day)</li>
                <li>Started piperacillin-tazobactam (Zosyn)</li>
                <li><strong>Rationale:</strong> WBC trending upward</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SLIDE 7 -->
    <div class="slide">
        <h1>Clinical Reasoning Challenge</h1>
        <div class="warning">
            <h3>When Lab and Clinical Picture Diverge - Which Do You Trust?</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="box" style="margin-top:20px;">
            <h3>Clinical Picture (Day 3)</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>✓ Weaned to room air</li>
                <li>✓ Afebrile × 72 hours</li>
                <li>✓ Hemodynamically stable</li>
                <li>✓ No respiratory distress</li>
                <li>✓ Creatinine improving</li>
                <li>✓ Patient feels well enough to demand discharge</li>
            </ul>
            <p style="margin-top:15px;font-weight:bold;">IDSA Guidelines: Clinical stability = treatment success</p>
        </div>
        <div class="critical" style="margin-top:20px;">
            <h3>Understanding WBC in CLL</h3>
            <p><strong>If CLL diagnosis had been recognized:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>WBC 14.98 represents <strong>baseline lymphocytosis from CLL</strong>, NOT treatment failure</li>
                <li>August labs: ALC was 3.48 K/µL (elevated baseline)</li>
                <li>Should have ordered <strong>CBC with differential</strong> to distinguish lymphocytes (CLL) vs neutrophils (infection)</li>
            </ul>
            <p style="margin-top:20px;font-weight:bold;font-size:1.2em;">Total WBC alone is insufficient - ALWAYS check differential</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SLIDE 8 -->
    <div class="slide">
        <h1>Teaching: Systematic Chart Review</h1>
        <div class="box">
            <h2>The SEARCH Mnemonic</h2>
            <p style="margin-bottom:20px;">Systematic approach to prevent missing critical information</p>
        </div>
        <div class="box">
            <p><strong>S</strong> - SEARCH systematically: Use EMR keywords ("biopsy," "flow cytometry," "hematology")</p>
        </div>
        <div class="box">
            <p><strong>E</strong> - EXAMINE problem list: Review both active AND inactive diagnoses</p>
        </div>
        <div class="box">
            <p><strong>A</strong> - ASK specific questions: "Ever had lymph node biopsy?" "See a cancer doctor?"</p>
        </div>
        <div class="box">
            <p><strong>R</strong> - REVIEW prior imaging: Compare current to prior - NEW vs CHRONIC changes management</p>
        </div>
        <div class="box">
            <p><strong>C</strong> - CHECK medications: Prophylactic antibiotics? Iron supplements? Why?</p>
        </div>
        <div class="box">
            <p><strong>H</strong> - HOSPITAL/specialty records: Search pathology, discharge summaries, subspecialty notes</p>
        </div>
        <div class="warning" style="margin-top:30px;">
            <p><strong>This case:</strong> Hematology note, flow cytometry, prior imaging all documented. Just needed systematic search.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SLIDE 9 -->
    <div class="slide">
        <h1>CLL & Infection Risk</h1>
        <div class="critical">
            <p style="font-size:1.3em;font-weight:bold;">Infection = LEADING cause of morbidity and mortality in CLL</p>
        </div>
        <div class="box" style="margin-top:20px;">
            <h3>Why CLL Patients Are Immunocompromised</h3>
            <p><strong>1. Hypogammaglobulinemia (50-80%):</strong> Decreased antibody production → S. pneumoniae, H. influenzae</p>
            <p><strong>2. T-cell dysfunction:</strong> Impaired cell-mediated immunity → Viral infections</p>
            <p><strong>3. Neutropenia:</strong> From disease or treatment</p>
            <p><strong>4. Complement deficiency:</strong> Further increases encapsulated organism risk</p>
        </div>
        <div class="box" style="margin-top:20px;">
            <h3>Management for Hospitalized CLL Patients</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Check immunoglobulins:</strong> IgG, IgA, IgM levels</li>
                <li><strong>IVIG candidate?</strong> If IgG <500 + recurrent infections</li>
                <li><strong>PJP prophylaxis:</strong> TMP-SMX if CD4 <200 or on treatment</li>
                <li><strong>Longer antibiotic course:</strong> 7-10 days vs 5 days for standard CAP</li>
                <li><strong>Coordinate with hematology</strong> before discharge</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SLIDE 10 -->
    <div class="slide">
        <h1>Antibiotic Stewardship</h1>
        <div class="box">
            <h3>IDSA/ATS CAP Guidelines - Clinical Stability Criteria</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>✓ Afebrile (Temp <100°F) × 48-72 hours</li>
                <li>✓ Hemodynamically stable</li>
                <li>✓ Improving oxygenation</li>
                <li>✓ Able to take oral medications</li>
                <li>✓ Normal mental status or return to baseline</li>
            </ul>
            <p style="margin-top:15px;font-weight:bold;">Standard duration: 5 days if clinically stable | Immunocompromised: 7-10 days</p>
        </div>
        <div class="box" style="margin-top:20px;">
            <h3>Initial Therapy (Day 1)</h3>
            <p><strong>Ceftriaxone + Azithromycin:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>✓ Appropriate for severe CAP</li>
                <li>✓ Covers typical + atypical</li>
                <li>✓ No renal adjustment needed</li>
                <li>✓ Cost-effective</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="warning" style="margin-top:20px;">
            <h3>Escalation (Day 3) to Zosyn</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Broad anti-pseudomonal coverage (not needed)</li>
                <li>Requires renal dose adjustment</li>
                <li>Higher cost, resistance pressure, C. diff risk</li>
            </ul>
            <p style="margin-top:15px;font-weight:bold;">When patient meets clinical stability criteria, continue effective therapy rather than escalating based on isolated lab changes</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SLIDE 11 -->
    <div class="slide">
        <h1>Care Coordination</h1>
        <div class="critical">
            <h3>A Missed Connection</h3>
            <p>Patient had <strong>active subspecialty care</strong> with scheduled follow-up. Hospitalization occurred when patient was <strong>due for his hematology appointment</strong>.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="box" style="margin-top:20px;">
            <h3>Timeline</h3>
            <p><strong>August 2025:</strong> Last hematology visit, patient stable, plan: "Return in 3 months"</p>
            <p><strong>November 2025:</strong> Patient admitted with pneumonia, missed scheduled appointment, subspecialty team unaware</p>
        </div>
        <div class="box" style="margin-top:20px;">
            <h3>Opportunities for Enhanced Coordination</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Search for recent subspecialty visits on admission</li>
                <li>Contact known subspecialists for complex patients</li>
                <li>Review appointment schedule for upcoming visits</li>
                <li>Coordinate discharge planning with established providers</li>
                <li>Ensure subspecialists aware of hospitalization</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SLIDE 12 -->
    <div class="slide">
        <h1>Systems Thinking</h1>
        <div class="box">
            <h3>Multiple Contributing Factors</h3>
            <p><strong>Patient-Level:</strong> Progressive dementia, lives alone, medication non-compliance</p>
            <p><strong>Provider-Level:</strong> Time constraints, cognitive biases, varying EMR proficiency</p>
            <p><strong>System-Level:</strong> Problem list maintenance, EMR design, lack of diagnostic reconciliation, workflow pressures</p>
        </div>
        <div class="warning" style="margin-top:20px;">
            <h3>Opportunities for System Improvement</h3>
            <p><strong>Technology:</strong> Enhanced clinical decision support, automated problem list updates, alerts for discordant data</p>
            <p><strong>Process:</strong> Diagnostic reconciliation (like med rec), structured admission workflows, protected chart review time</p>
            <p><strong>Culture:</strong> Environment where discussing errors is encouraged, non-punitive, focused on learning</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SLIDE 13 -->
    <div class="slide">
        <h1>Immediate Actions (3:51 AM)</h1>
        <div class="box">
            <h3>DO NOW (Next 30 minutes):</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>✓ Update problem list: Add CLL/SLL Stage III</li>
                <li>✓ Write overnight note documenting discovery</li>
                <li>✓ Add labs to morning orders: CBC w/ diff, IgG/IgA/IgM, LDH, CD4</li>
                <li>✓ Brief senior resident or covering attending</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="box" style="margin-top:20px;">
            <h3>DO AT 8 AM:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Place STAT hematology consult</li>
                <li>Discuss at morning rounds with attending</li>
                <li>Review lab results</li>
                <li>Call patient's established hematologist</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="box" style="margin-top:20px;">
            <h3>DO BEFORE DISCHARGE:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Hematology recommendations obtained</li>
                <li>Prophylaxis plan established (TMP-SMX if indicated)</li>
                <li>Safe discharge coordination</li>
                <li>Follow-up scheduled with hematology</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SLIDE 14 -->
    <div class="slide">
        <h1>Key Takeaways</h1>
        <div class="box">
            <p><strong>1. Comprehensive Chart Review:</strong> Use SEARCH mnemonic. Critical information usually in chart.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="box">
            <p><strong>2. CLL = Immunocompromised:</strong> Infection leading cause of morbidity. Check IgG, prophylaxis, coordinate care.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="box">
            <p><strong>3. Clinical Picture > Labs:</strong> Clinical stability = success (IDSA). WBC normalization not required. Always check differential.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="box">
            <p><strong>4. Stewardship in Complex Patients:</strong> Appropriate empiric therapy. Avoid unnecessary escalation in improving patients.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="box">
            <p><strong>5. Care Coordination:</strong> Contact subspecialists. This patient missed hematology appointment due to hospitalization.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="box">
            <p><strong>6. Systems Thinking:</strong> Multiple factors contribute. Focus on system improvements, not blame. Create learning culture.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SLIDE 15 -->
    <div class="slide">
        <h1>Conclusion</h1>
        <div class="box">
            <h3>Case Summary</h3>
            <p>82-year-old male with recurrent pneumonia demonstrates complexity of modern medical care and importance of systematic approaches to information gathering, clinical reasoning, and care coordination.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="warning" style="margin-top:30px;">
            <h3>What We Learned</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Value of comprehensive chart review using systematic approaches</li>
                <li>How to recognize and manage immunocompromised patients</li>
                <li>When to trust clinical picture over isolated lab values</li>
                <li>How to apply stewardship in complex cases</li>
                <li>Critical importance of care coordination</li>
                <li>How systems thinking prevents future gaps</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="critical" style="margin-top:30px;text-align:center;">
            <h2>Focus on Learning and Systems Improvement</h2>
            <p style="font-size:1.2em;margin-top:15px;">Excellence in medicine requires both individual diligence and robust systems that support comprehensive care</p>
        </div>
    </div>

